          <h5>Introduction </h5>
          <p>Survey is a universal and simple way of collecting huge amount of data in relatively short amount of time. However, according to my experience, conducting an effective survey is even more difficult than other user research technique. Researchers have to be really careful about all the words put on, structure, order and lots of other details. </p>        
          <p>Recently I have been reading research papers about standardized questionnaires and the book, quantifying user experience. Here are a summary of some useful notes and thoughts I got from the readings. </p>
          <h5>Advantage of applying standardized survey design</h5>
          <ul>
            <li>Objectivity</li>
            <li>Replicability</li>
            <li>Quantification</li>
            <li>Economy</li>
            <li>Communication</li>
            <li>Scientific generalization</li>
          </ul>
          <h5> SUS</h5>
          <ul>
            <li> Fee:0 USD </li>
            <li> 10 questions</li>
            <li>Five point scale (Strongly disagree to strongly agree<li>
            <li>Handy benchmarks</li>
            <li> 12 to 15 samples is doing well on representing the whole data set</li>
            <li> Global Reliability= 0.92</li>
          </ul>
          <h5> QUIS</h5>
          <ul>
            <li>Fee: 50-750 USD required</li>
            <li> 28 questions</li>
            <li> Ten point scale (Terrible to Wonderful)</li>
            <li> Global Reliability: 0.94</li>
          </ul>
          <h5> CSUQ (A variant of PSSUQ) </h5>
          <ul>
            <li>19 Qeustions</li>
            <li>Seven pomt scale(Strongly agree to disagree)</li>
            <li> 12 samples can represent about 90% datasets</li>
            <li>Global Reliability= 0.94 </li>
          </ul>
          <img src='pic/chart.jpg' width='80%'>
          <h5> Reference</h5>
          <ul>
            <li>Objectivity</li>
            <li>Replicability</li>
            <li>Quantification</li>
            <li>Economy</li>
            <li>Communication</li>
            <li>Scientific generalization</li>
          </ul> 
        </div>
